===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|kednei|lang=enm}}, {{term|kidenei|||lang=enm}}, from earlier {{term|kidnere|kidnēre|lang=enm}}, {{term|kidenere|kidenēre|kidney|lang=enm}}. Of uncertain origin. Probably a compound consisting of {{etyl|enm|-}} *{{term||kid-, *quid-|belly, womb|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|cwiþ|lang=ang}}, {{term|cwiþa||belly, womb, stomach|lang=ang}} + {{etyl|enm}} {{term|nere|nēre|kidney|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} *{{term||nēore|kidney|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|neuran|kidney|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|negʷh-r-|kidney|lang=en}}. If so, then related to {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|nier||kidney|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Niere||kidney|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|nyre||kidney|lang=da}}.

Alternate etymology traces the first element to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|ceod|cēod|lang=ang}}, {{term|codd||sack, scrotum|lang=ang}}, as the terms for testicle and kidney were often interchangeable in Germanic (compare {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|nioro||kidney", also "testicle|lang=goh}}, Old {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|vigniauri|vig-niauri|testicle|lang=sv}}. More at {{l|en|codpiece}}.

